Windows Server 2022 — Domain Controller Setup

Complete walkthrough for installing and configuring Windows Server 2022 as the domain controller (DC) for corp.local domain.


Installation & Network Configuration

Install Windows Server 2022


Create a new VM in VirtualBox: DC01

RAM: 4096 MB minimum
CPU: 2 cores
Disk: 60 GB
Network: Host-only Adapter → vboxnet0



Boot from Windows Server 2022 ISO
Choose Windows Server 2022 Standard Evaluation (Desktop Experience)
Complete installation with custom disk setup
Set Administrator password: Lab@Secure2024!
Rename computer to DC01


Configure Static IP Address

The domain controller must have a fixed IP address — if it changes, the entire domain breaks.

Using PowerShell:

powershellNew-NetIPAddress -InterfaceAlias Ethernet -IPAddress 192.168.10.10 -PrefixLength 24 -DefaultGateway 192.168.10.1

What it does:


-IPAddress 192.168.10.10 = this server's static IP
-PrefixLength 24 = subnet mask 255.255.255.0 (/24)
-DefaultGateway 192.168.10.1 = pfSense is the gateway


Set DNS to point to itself (after AD install, this server becomes the DNS server):

powershellSet-DnsClientServerAddress -InterfaceAlias Ethernet -ServerAddresses 127.0.0.1

Add the default route for internet traffic:

powershellNew-NetRoute -DestinationPrefix 0.0.0.0/0 -NextHop 192.168.10.1 -InterfaceAlias Ethernet -RouteMetric 256

Verify Network Connectivity

powershellping 192.168.10.1

Should get replies from pfSense. Then verify internet:

powershellping 8.8.8.8

Both pings must succeed before proceeding.


Install Active Directory Domain Services

Install AD DS Role

Open PowerShell as Administrator and run:

powershellInstall-WindowsFeature -Name AD-Domain-Services -IncludeManagementTools

What it does:


-Name AD-Domain-Services = install the Active Directory Domain Services role
-IncludeManagementTools = also install tools to manage AD (Active Directory Users and Computers, etc.)


Expected output: "Success: True" after 2-3 minutes

Promote to Domain Controller

powershellInstall-ADDSForest -DomainName corp.local -SafeModeAdministratorPassword (ConvertTo-SecureString "Lab@Secure2024!" -AsPlainText -Force) -Force -NoRebootOnCompletion

What each part does:


Install-ADDSForest = create new Active Directory forest and promote this server to domain controller
-DomainName corp.local = create domain named "corp.local" (your internal company domain)
-SafeModeAdministratorPassword = set Directory Services Restore Mode (DSRM) password for disaster recovery
-Force = don't ask for confirmation
-NoRebootOnCompletion = install but don't auto-reboot


Expected output: Takes 3-5 minutes. Warnings about cryptography and DNS delegation are normal and safe to ignore in a lab environment.

Restart Server

powershellRestart-Computer

Server reboots and all Active Directory services load.

Verify Active Directory is Working

After reboot, run:

powershellGet-ADDomain

Expected output shows:


Name: corp — your domain short name
Forest: corp.local — your domain's full name
PDCEmulator: DC01.corp.local — DC01 is the primary domain controller
DomainMode: Windows2016Domain — domain functional level



Create Active Directory Structure

Create Organizational Units (OUs)

OUs are folders in Active Directory that organize users and computers by department or function.

powershellNew-ADOrganizationalUnit -Name "Staff" -Path "DC=corp,DC=local"

powershellNew-ADOrganizationalUnit -Name "IT_Admins" -Path "DC=corp,DC=local"

What it does:


-Name "Staff" = create OU named "Staff"
-Path "DC=corp,DC=local" = place it at the top level of corp.local domain


Create User Accounts

User 1: John Smith

powershellNew-ADUser -Name "John Smith" -GivenName "John" -Surname "Smith" -SamAccountName "jsmith" -UserPrincipalName "jsmith@corp.local" -Path "OU=Staff,DC=corp,DC=local" -AccountPassword (ConvertTo-SecureString "UserPass@123" -AsPlainText -Force) -Enabled $true

User 2: Amy Jones

powershellNew-ADUser -Name "Amy Jones" -GivenName "Amy" -Surname "Jones" -SamAccountName "ajones" -UserPrincipalName "ajones@corp.local" -Path "OU=Staff,DC=corp,DC=local" -AccountPassword (ConvertTo-SecureString "UserPass@123" -AsPlainText -Force) -Enabled $true

User 3: Bob Wilson

powershellNew-ADUser -Name "Bob Wilson" -GivenName "Bob" -Surname "Wilson" -SamAccountName "bwilson" -UserPrincipalName "bwilson@corp.local" -Path "OU=Staff,DC=corp,DC=local" -AccountPassword (ConvertTo-SecureString "UserPass@123" -AsPlainText -Force) -Enabled $true

What each part does:


-Name "John Smith" = display name in Active Directory
-SamAccountName "jsmith" = username for login (short name)
-UserPrincipalName "jsmith@corp.local" = email-style login name
-Path "OU=Staff,DC=corp,DC=local" = place user in Staff OU
-AccountPassword (ConvertTo-SecureString "UserPass@123" -AsPlainText -Force) = set password in secure format
-Enabled $true = account is active immediately


Create Security Group

powershellNew-ADGroup -Name "Domain_Staff" -SamAccountName "Domain_Staff" -GroupCategory Security -GroupScope Global -Path "OU=Staff,DC=corp,DC=local"

What it does:


-GroupCategory Security = this group controls access to resources
-GroupScope Global = can be used throughout the entire forest
-Path "OU=Staff,DC=corp,DC=local" = place group in Staff OU


Add Users to Group

powershellAdd-ADGroupMember -Identity "Domain_Staff" -Members "jsmith", "ajones", "bwilson"

This allows you to apply policies to the entire group instead of individual users.


Verification & Testing

List All OUs

powershellGet-ADOrganizationalUnit -Filter "Name -like '*'"

Should show: Staff, IT_Admins

List All Users in Staff OU

powershellGet-ADUser -Filter "Name -like '*'" -SearchBase "OU=Staff,DC=corp,DC=local"

Should show: jsmith, ajones, bwilson with UserPrincipalName and SID for each

List Group Members

powershellGet-ADGroupMember -Identity "Domain_Staff"

Should show: All three users


What Was Built

Your DC01 now runs:


Active Directory — manages user accounts, groups, computers, and policies
DNS Server — resolves corp.local hostnames internally and forwards external queries to the internet
DHCP Server — automatically assigns IP addresses to machines on the network (via pfSense configuration)


This is the brain of your entire lab network. Every other machine will connect to it, authenticate through it, and receive policies from it.


Why This Matters

When you later boot a Windows 10 workstation:


It searches DNS for "corp.local"
DNS (running on DC01) responds with 192.168.10.10
Workstation connects and joins the domain
Users can log in with domain accounts (jsmith, ajones, bwilson)
Group policies automatically apply to the workstation
All machines are centrally managed


This is exactly how enterprise networks operate — DC01 is the foundation.


Common Issues & Fixes

Problem: Can't ping pfSense after setting static IP

Solution: The default route may not have been created. Run:

powershellNew-NetRoute -DestinationPrefix 0.0.0.0/0 -NextHop 192.168.10.1 -InterfaceAlias Ethernet -RouteMetric 256

Problem: AD install fails with DNS errors

Solution: DNS errors during AD promotion are normal. Verify AD installed correctly with Get-ADDomain.

Problem: Can't create users — "Access Denied"

Solution: You must be running PowerShell as Administrator. Right-click PowerShell → "Run as Administrator".
